th the contemporary condition of the regions, states and localities - the ideal American space with its reality as a place. It uses the public standard provided by the official ideology of the United States to see how well things are really going.The authors consider the contrast between ideal and reality at local, state, and national levels in education, health, and welfare, in community, race, gender, and class relations, in economic and industrial development, and in the use and exploitation of America's landscape. Each chapter addresses the issues through evidence of long-term and recent trends, and grounds its arguments in information.American Space/American Place provides a series of compelling insights into the current condition of American society, its natural environment, and its place within the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGeographyxPhilosophy. 0aGeographyxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aGeographyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aGeographyzUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Paul C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgnew, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, James S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForest, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJonas, Andrew E. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKodras, Janet E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRigby, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharp, Joanne P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aS